# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andinobates-cassidyhornae
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] Since the launch of the site in 2008, the number of users has grown rapidly, reaching about 10 million daily visits in early 2022.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] By 2024, Academia.edu has over 270 million registered users, with over 55 million papers currently available on the platform.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] In 2022, the company entered the scientific publishing sector, launching a dozen scientific, open access journals, and publishing under the name of Academia.edu Journals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] Academia.edu was founded by Richard Price in 2008.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] On its filings with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the company uses the legal name Academia Inc.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] The site was registered in the .edu top-level domain in 1999 when that domain was not limited to educational institutions.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] In 2013, Elsevier sent thousands of takedown notices to Academia.edu, claiming copyright infringement for Elsevier-published content that was posted on Academia.edu.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] Following widespread complaint of these takedown notices, Elsevier retracted their request, and academics were allowed to continue to post their publications.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] Critics mention several alternatives for free access publications for people who want to make their work freely available.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] Many universities and educational consortia have their own institutional repositories, including the Big Ten Academic Alliance.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] Zenodo (funded by The OpenAIRE Consortium) and Humanities Commons both work to keep humanities scholarship online without monetizing it.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] Academia.edu's competitors include ResearchGate, Google Scholar and Mendeley.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] In 2016 Academia.edu reportedly had more registered users than ResearchGate (about 34 million versus 11 million) and higher web traffic, but ResearchGate had substantially more active usage by researchers.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] In 2020, the traffic ranks had reversed, with ResearchGate ranked in the top 150–200 websites globally according to Alexa Internet, whereas Academia.edu was positioned in the 200–300 range.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] Unpaywall, which collects data about open access versions of academic publications and provides easy access to them, is also considered a competitor to Academia.edu.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] As of December 2025, Academia.edu Journals has launched 18 open-access journals that publish articles in various scientific fields, including medicine.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] As a gold open-access publisher, all articles are freely available.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] All journals waived article processing charges for authors during the year in which the journal was launched, and continue to waive these fees for authors who come from eligible countries or can prove difficulty with paying due to lack of funding.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] Academia.edu is not a university or institution for higher learning and so under current standards it would not qualify for the ".edu" top-level domain.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] However, since the domain name "Academia.edu" was registered in 1999, before the regulations required .edu domain names to be held solely by accredited post-secondary institutions in the US, it is allowed to remain active and operational.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] All .edu domain names registered before 2001 were grandfathered in, even if not an accredited USA post-secondary institution.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] Academia.edu claims it supports the open science or open access movements and, in particular, instant distribution of research, and a peer-review system that occurs alongside distribution, instead of before it.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] Accordingly, the company stated its opposition to the proposed (since withdrawn) 2011 U.S.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] Research Works Act, which would have prevented open-access mandates in the U.S.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] However, in the view of critic Peter Suber, Academia.edu is not an open access repository and is not recommended as a way to pursue green open access.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] Peter Suber instead invites researchers to use field-specific repositories or general-purpose repositories like Zenodo.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] In early 2016, some users reported having received e-mails from Academia.edu where they were asked if they would be interested in paying a fee to have their papers recommended by the website's editors.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] This led some users to start a campaign encouraging users to cancel their Academia.edu accounts.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] Other criticisms include the fact that Academia.edu uses a vendor lock-in model: "It's up to Academia.edu to decide what you can and can't do with the information you've given them, and they're not likely to make it easy for alternative methods to access".
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] This is in reference to the fact that, although papers can be read by non-users, a free account is needed in order to download papers: "you need to be logged in to do most of the useful things on the site (even as a casual reader)".
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] In December 2016, Academia.edu announced new premium features that includes data analytics on work and the professional rank of the viewers, which have also received criticism.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/academia-edu] This strategy, where key financial terms are presented in visually muted text with low contrast, is viewed as a violation of transaction transparency principles and consumer protection standards.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Young amphibians generally undergo metamorphosis from an aquatic larval form with gills to an air-breathing adult form with lungs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Amphibians use their skin as a secondary respiratory interface, and some small terrestrial salamanders and frogs even lack lungs and rely entirely on their skin.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They are superficially similar to reptiles like lizards, but unlike reptiles and other amniotes, require access to water bodies to breed.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] With their complex reproductive needs and permeable skins, amphibians are often ecological indicators to habitat conditions; in recent decades there has been a dramatic decline in amphibian populations for many species around the globe.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Contrary to a common misconception, adult amphibians generally cannot breathe underwater.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Wildlife hospitals report that a frequent mistake made by people who bring frogs and toads for treatment is placing them in water-filled aquaria without providing a means of exit.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The earliest amphibians evolved in the Devonian period from tetrapodomorph sarcopterygians (lobe-finned fish with articulated limb-like fins) that evolved primitive lungs, which were helpful in adapting to dry land.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They diversified and became ecologically dominant during the Carboniferous and Permian periods, but were later displaced in terrestrial environments by early reptiles and basal synapsids (predecessors of mammals).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The origin of modern lissamphibians, which first appeared during the Early Triassic, around 250 million years ago, has long been contentious.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The most popular hypothesis is that they likely originated from temnospondyls, the most diverse group of prehistoric amphibians, during the Permian period.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Another hypothesis is that they emerged from lepospondyls.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] A fourth group of lissamphibians, the Albanerpetontidae, became extinct around 2 million years ago.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The number of known amphibian species is approximately 8,000, of which nearly 90% are frogs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The smallest amphibian (and vertebrate) in the world is a frog from New Guinea (*Paedophryne amauensis*) with a length of just 7.7 mm (0.30 in).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The largest living amphibian is the 1.8 m (5 ft 11 in) South China giant salamander (*Andrias sligoi*), but this is dwarfed by prehistoric temnospondyls such as *Mastodonsaurus* which could reach up to 6 m (20 ft) in length.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The study of amphibians is called batrachology, while the study of both reptiles and amphibians is called herpetology.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The word *amphibian* is derived from the Ancient Greek term ἀμφίβιος (*amphíbios*), which means 'both kinds of life', ἀμφί meaning 'of both kinds' and βίος meaning 'life'.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The term was initially used as a general adjective for animals that could live on land or in water, including seals and otters.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Traditionally, the class Amphibia includes all tetrapod vertebrates that are not amniotes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The actual number of species in each group depends on the taxonomic classification followed.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The two most common systems are the classification adopted by the website AmphibiaWeb, University of California, Berkeley, and the classification by herpetologist Darrel Frost and the American Museum of Natural History, available as the online reference database "Amphibian Species of the World".
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The numbers of species cited above follows Frost and the total number of known (living) amphibian species as of 31 March 2019, is exactly 8,000, of which nearly 90% are frogs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] With the phylogenetic classification, the taxon Labyrinthodontia has been discarded as it is a polyparaphyletic group without unique defining features apart from shared primitive characteristics.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Classification varies according to the preferred phylogeny of the author and whether they use a stem-based or a node-based classification.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Traditionally, amphibians as a class are defined as all tetrapods with a larval stage, while the group that includes the common ancestors of all living amphibians (frogs, salamanders and caecilians) and all their descendants is called Lissamphibia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The phylogeny of Paleozoic amphibians is uncertain, and Lissamphibia may possibly fall within extinct groups, like the Temnospondyli (traditionally placed in the subclass Labyrinthodontia) or the Lepospondyli, and in some analyses even in the amniotes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] This means that advocates of phylogenetic nomenclature have removed a large number of basal Devonian and Carboniferous amphibian-type tetrapod groups that were formerly placed in Amphibia in Linnaean taxonomy, and included them elsewhere under cladistic taxonomy.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] If the common ancestor of amphibians and amniotes is included in Amphibia, it becomes a paraphyletic group.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] All modern amphibians are included in the subclass Lissamphibia, which is usually considered a clade, a group of species that have evolved from a common ancestor.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The three modern orders are Anura (the frogs), Caudata (or Urodela, the salamanders), and Gymnophiona (or Apoda, the caecilians).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] It has been suggested that salamanders arose separately from a temnospondyl-like ancestor, and even that caecilians are the sister group of the advanced reptiliomorph amphibians, and thus of amniotes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Although the fossils of several older proto-frogs with primitive characteristics are known, the oldest "true frog", with hopping adaptations is *Prosalirus bitis*, from the Early Jurassic Kayenta Formation of Arizona.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] It is anatomically very similar to modern frogs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The oldest known caecilians are *Funcusvermis gilmorei* (from the Late Triassic) and *Eocaecilia micropodia* (from the Early Jurassic), both from Arizona.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The earliest salamander is *Beiyanerpeton jianpingensis* from the Late Jurassic of northeastern China.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Authorities disagree as to whether Salientia is a superorder that includes the order Anura, or whether Anura is a sub-order of the order Salientia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The Lissamphibia are traditionally divided into three orders, but an extinct salamander-like family, the Albanerpetontidae, is now considered part of Lissamphibia alongside the superorder Salientia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Furthermore, Salientia includes all three recent orders plus the Triassic proto-frog, *Triadobatrachus*.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The first major groups of amphibians developed in the Devonian period, around 370 million years ago, from lobe-finned fish which were similar to the modern coelacanth and lungfish.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] These ancient lobe-finned fish had evolved multi-jointed leg-like fins with digits that enabled them to crawl along the sea bottom.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Some fish had developed primitive lungs that help them breathe air when the stagnant pools of the Devonian swamps were low in oxygen.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They could also use their strong fins to hoist themselves out of the water and onto dry land if circumstances so required.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Eventually, their bony fins would evolve into limbs and they would become the ancestors to all tetrapods, including modern amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Despite being able to crawl on land, many of these prehistoric tetrapodomorph fish still spent most of their time in the water.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They had started to develop lungs, but still breathed predominantly with gills.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Many examples of species showing transitional features have been discovered.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] *Ichthyostega* was one of the first primitive amphibians, with nostrils and more efficient lungs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] It had four sturdy limbs, a neck, a tail with fins and a skull very similar to that of the lobe-finned fish, *Eusthenopteron*.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Amphibians evolved adaptations that allowed them to stay out of the water for longer periods.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Their lungs improved and their skeletons became heavier and stronger, better able to support the weight of their bodies on land.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They developed "hands" and "feet" with five or more digits; the skin became more capable of retaining body fluids and resisting desiccation.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The fish's hyomandibula bone in the hyoid region behind the gills diminished in size and became the stapes of the amphibian ear, an adaptation necessary for hearing on dry land.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] An affinity between the amphibians and the teleost fish is the multi-folded structure of the teeth and the paired supra-occipital bones at the back of the head, neither of these features being found elsewhere in the animal kingdom.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] At the end of the Devonian period (360 million years ago), the seas, rivers and lakes were teeming with life while the land was the realm of early plants and devoid of vertebrates, though some, such as *Ichthyostega*, may have sometimes hauled themselves out of the water.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] It is thought they may have propelled themselves with their forelimbs, dragging their hindquarters in a similar manner to that used by the elephant seal.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In the early Carboniferous (360 to 323 million years ago), the climate was relatively wet and warm.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Extensive swamps developed with mosses, ferns, horsetails and calamites.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Air-breathing arthropods evolved and invaded the land where they provided food for the carnivorous amphibians that began to adapt to the terrestrial environment.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] There were no other tetrapods on the land and the amphibians were at the top of the food chain, with some occupying ecological positions currently held by crocodiles.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Though equipped with limbs and the ability to breathe air, most still had a long tapering body and strong tail.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Others were the top land predators, sometimes reaching several metres in length, preying on the large insects of the period and the many types of fish in the water.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They still needed to return to water to lay their shell-less eggs, and even most modern amphibians have a fully aquatic larval stage with gills like their fish ancestors.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] It was the development of the amniotic egg, which prevents the developing embryo from drying out, that enabled the reptiles to reproduce on land and which led to their dominance in the period that followed.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] After the Carboniferous rainforest collapse amphibian dominance gave way to reptiles, and amphibians were further devastated by the Permian–Triassic extinction event.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] During the Triassic Period (252 to 201 million years ago), the reptiles continued to out-compete the amphibians, leading to a reduction in both the amphibians' size and their importance in the biosphere.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] According to the fossil record, Lissamphibia, which includes all modern amphibians and is the only surviving lineage, may have branched off from the extinct groups Temnospondyli and Lepospondyli at some period between the Late Carboniferous and the Early Triassic.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The relative scarcity of fossil evidence precludes precise dating, but the most recent molecular study, based on multilocus sequence typing, suggests a Late Carboniferous/Early Permian origin for extant amphibians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The origins and evolutionary relationships between the three main groups of amphibians is a matter of debate.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] A 2005 molecular phylogeny, based on rDNA analysis, suggests that salamanders and caecilians are more closely related to each other than they are to frogs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] It also appears that the divergence of the three groups took place in the Paleozoic or early Mesozoic (around 250 million years ago), before the breakup of the supercontinent Pangaea and soon after their divergence from the lobe-finned fish.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The briefness of this period, and the swiftness with which radiation took place, would help account for the relative scarcity of primitive amphibian fossils.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] There are large gaps in the fossil record, the discovery of the dissorophoid temnospondyl *Gerobatrachus* from the Early Permian in Texas in 2008 provided a missing link with many of the characteristics of modern frogs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Molecular analysis suggests that the frog–salamander divergence took place considerably earlier than the palaeontological evidence indicates.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] One study suggested that the last common ancestor of all modern amphibians lived about 315 million years ago, and that stereospondyl temnospondyls are the closest relatives to the caecilians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] However, most studies support a single monophyletic origin of all modern amphibians within the dissorophoid temnospondyls.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] As they evolved from lunged fish, amphibians had to make certain adaptations for living on land, including the need to develop new means of locomotion.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In the water, the sideways thrusts of their tails had propelled them forward, but on land, quite different mechanisms were required.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Their vertebral columns, limbs, limb girdles and musculature needed to be strong enough to raise them off the ground for locomotion and feeding.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Terrestrial adults discarded their lateral line systems and adapted their sensory systems to receive stimuli via the medium of the air.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They needed to develop new methods to regulate their body heat to cope with fluctuations in ambient temperature.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They developed behaviours suitable for reproduction in a terrestrial environment.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Their skins were exposed to harmful ultraviolet rays that had previously been absorbed by the water.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The skin changed to become more protective and prevent excessive water loss.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The superclass Tetrapoda is divided into four classes of vertebrate animals with four limbs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Reptiles, birds and mammals are amniotes, the eggs of which are either laid or carried by the female and are surrounded by several membranes, some of which are impervious.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Lacking these membranes, amphibians require water bodies for reproduction, although some species have developed various strategies for protecting or bypassing the vulnerable aquatic larval stage.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They are not found in the sea with the exception of one or two frogs that live in brackish water in mangrove swamps; the Anderson's salamander meanwhile occurs in brackish or salt water lakes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] On land, amphibians are restricted to moist habitats because of the need to keep their skin damp.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Modern amphibians have a simplified anatomy compared to their ancestors due to paedomorphosis, caused by two evolutionary trends: miniaturization and an unusually large genome, which result in a slower growth and development rate compared to other vertebrates.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Another reason for their size is associated with their rapid metamorphosis, which seems to have evolved only in the ancestors of Lissamphibia; in all other known lines the development was much more gradual.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Because a remodeling of the feeding apparatus means they do not eat during the metamorphosis, the metamorphosis has to go faster the smaller the individual is, so it happens at an early stage when the larvae are still small.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] (The largest species of salamanders do not go through a metamorphosis.) Amphibians that lay eggs on land often go through the whole metamorphosis inside the egg.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] An anamniotic terrestrial egg is less than 1 cm in diameter due to diffusion problems, a size which puts a limit on the amount of posthatching growth.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The smallest amphibian (and vertebrate) in the world is a microhylid frog from New Guinea (*Paedophryne amauensis*) first discovered in 2012.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] It has an average length of 7.7 mm (0.30 in) and is part of a genus that contains four of the world's ten smallest frog species.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The largest frog is the African Goliath frog (*Conraua goliath*), which can reach 32 cm (13 in) and weigh 3 kg (6.6 lb).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Amphibians are ectothermic (cold-blooded) vertebrates that do not maintain their body temperature through internal physiological processes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Their metabolic rate is low and as a result, their food and energy requirements are limited.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In the adult state, they have tear ducts and movable eyelids, and most species have ears that can detect airborne or ground vibrations.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They have muscular tongues, which in many species can be protruded.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Modern amphibians have fully ossified vertebrae with articular processes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Their ribs are usually short and may be fused to the vertebrae.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Their skulls are mostly broad and short, and are often incompletely ossified.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Their skin contains little keratin and lacks scales, apart from a few fish-like scales in certain caecilians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The skin contains many mucous glands and in some species, poison glands (a type of granular gland).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The hearts of amphibians have three chambers, two atria and one ventricle.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They have a urinary bladder and nitrogenous waste products are excreted primarily as urea.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Most amphibians lay their eggs in water and have aquatic larvae that undergo metamorphosis to become terrestrial adults.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Amphibians breathe by means of a pump action in which air is first drawn into the buccopharyngeal region through the nostrils.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] These are then closed and the air is forced into the lungs by contraction of the throat.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They supplement this with gas exchange through the skin.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The order Anura (from the Ancient Greek *a(n)-* meaning "without" and *oura* meaning "tail") comprises the frogs and toads.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They usually have long hind limbs that fold underneath them, shorter forelimbs, webbed toes with no claws, no tails, large eyes and glandular moist skin.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Members of this order with smooth skins are commonly referred to as frogs, while those with warty skins are known as toads.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The difference is not a formal one taxonomically and there are numerous exceptions to this rule.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Members of the family Bufonidae are known as the "true toads".
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Frogs range in size from the 30-centimetre (12 in) Goliath frog (*Conraua goliath*) of West Africa to the 7.7-millimetre (0.30 in) *Paedophryne amauensis*, first described in Papua New Guinea in 2012, which is also the smallest known vertebrate.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Although most species are associated with water and damp habitats, some are specialised to live in trees or in deserts.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They are found worldwide except for polar areas.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Anura is divided into three suborders that are broadly accepted by the scientific community, but the relationships between some families remain unclear.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Future molecular studies should provide further insights into their evolutionary relationships.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The suborder Archaeobatrachia contains four families of primitive frogs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] These are Ascaphidae, Bombinatoridae, Discoglossidae and Leiopelmatidae which have few derived features and are probably paraphyletic with regard to other frog lineages.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The six families in the more evolutionarily advanced suborder Mesobatrachia are the fossorial Megophryidae, Pelobatidae, Pelodytidae, Scaphiopodidae and Rhinophrynidae and the obligatorily aquatic Pipidae.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] These have certain characteristics that are intermediate between the two other suborders.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Neobatrachia is by far the largest suborder and includes the remaining families of modern frogs, including most common species.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Approximately 96% of the over 5,000 extant species of frog are neobatrachians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The order Caudata (from the Latin *cauda* meaning "tail") consists of the salamanders—elongated, low-slung animals that mostly resemble lizards in form.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] This is a symplesiomorphic trait and they are no more closely related to lizards than they are to mammals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Salamanders lack claws, have scale-free skins, either smooth or covered with tubercles, and tails that are usually flattened from side to side and often finned.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They range in size from the Chinese giant salamander (*Andrias davidianus*), which has been reported to grow to a length of 1.8 metres (5 ft 11 in), to the diminutive *Thorius pennatulus* from Mexico which seldom exceeds 20 mm (0.8 in) in length.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Salamanders have a mostly Laurasian distribution, being present in much of the Holarctic region of the northern hemisphere.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The family Plethodontidae is also found in Central America and South America north of the Amazon basin; South America was apparently invaded from Central America by about the start of the Miocene, 23 million years ago.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Urodela is a name sometimes used for all the extant species of salamanders.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Members of several salamander families have become paedomorphic and either fail to complete their metamorphosis or retain some larval characteristics as adults.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Most salamanders are under 15 cm (5.9 in) long.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They may be terrestrial or aquatic and many spend part of the year in each habitat.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] When on land, they mostly spend the day hidden under stones or logs or in dense vegetation, emerging in the evening and night to forage for worms, insects and other invertebrates.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The suborder Cryptobranchoidea contains the primitive salamanders.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] A number of fossil cryptobranchids have been found, but there are only three living species, the Chinese giant salamander (*Andrias davidianus*), the Japanese giant salamander (*Andrias japonicus*) and the hellbender (*Cryptobranchus alleganiensis*) from North America.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] These large amphibians retain several larval characteristics in their adult state; gills slits are present and the eyes are unlidded.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] A unique feature is their ability to feed by suction, depressing either the left side of their lower jaw or the right.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The males excavate nests, persuade females to lay their egg strings inside them, and guard them.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] As well as breathing with lungs, they respire through the many folds in their thin skin, which has capillaries close to the surface.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The suborder Salamandroidea contains the advanced salamanders.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They differ from the cryptobranchids by having fused prearticular bones in the lower jaw, and by using internal fertilisation.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In salamandrids, the male deposits a bundle of sperm, the spermatophore, and the female picks it up and inserts it into her cloaca where the sperm is stored until the eggs are laid.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The largest family in this group is Plethodontidae, the lungless salamanders, which includes 60% of all salamander species.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The family Salamandridae includes the true salamanders and the name "newt" is given to members of its subfamily Pleurodelinae.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The third suborder, Sirenoidea, contains the four species of sirens, which are in a single family, Sirenidae.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Members of this order are eel-like aquatic salamanders with much reduced forelimbs and no hind limbs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Some of their features are primitive while others are derived.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Fertilisation is likely to be external as sirenids lack the cloacal glands used by male salamandrids to produce spermatophores and the females lack spermathecae for sperm storage.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Despite this, the eggs are laid singly, a behaviour not conducive for external fertilisation.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The order Gymnophiona (from the Greek *gymnos* meaning "naked" and *ophis* meaning "serpent") or Apoda comprises the caecilians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] These are long, cylindrical, limbless animals with a snake- or worm-like form.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The adults vary in length from 8 to 75 centimetres (3 to 30 inches) with the exception of Thomson's caecilian (*Caecilia thompsoni*), which can reach 150 cm (59 in).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] A caecilian's skin has a large number of transverse folds and in some species contains tiny embedded dermal scales.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] It has rudimentary eyes covered in skin, which are probably limited to discerning differences in light intensity.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] It also has a pair of short tentacles near the eye that can be extended and which have tactile and olfactory functions.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Most caecilians live underground in burrows in damp soil, in rotten wood and under plant debris, but some are aquatic.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Most species lay their eggs underground and when the larvae hatch, they make their way to adjacent bodies of water.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Others brood their eggs and the larvae undergo metamorphosis before the eggs hatch.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] A few species give birth to live young, nourishing them with glandular secretions while they are in the oviduct.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Caecilians have a mostly Gondwanan distribution, being found in tropical regions of Africa, Asia and Central and South America.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The integumentary structure contains some typical characteristics common to terrestrial vertebrates, such as the presence of highly cornified outer layers, renewed periodically through a moulting process controlled by the pituitary and thyroid glands.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Local thickenings (often called warts) are common, such as those found on toads.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The outside of the skin is shed periodically mostly in one piece, in contrast to mammals and birds where it is shed in flakes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Caecilians are unique among amphibians in having mineralized dermal scales embedded in the dermis between the furrows in the skin.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The similarity of these to the scales of bony fish is largely superficial.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Lizards and some frogs have somewhat similar osteoderms forming bony deposits in the dermis, but this is an example of convergent evolution with similar structures having arisen independently in diverse vertebrate lineages.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Gas exchange can take place through the skin (cutaneous respiration) and this allows adult amphibians to respire without-rising to the surface of water and to hibernate at the bottom of ponds.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] To compensate for their thin and delicate skin, amphibians have evolved mucous glands, principally on their heads, backs and tails.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The secretions produced by these help keep the skin moist.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In addition, most species of amphibian have granular glands that secrete distasteful or poisonous substances.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Some amphibian toxins can be lethal to humans while others have little effect.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The main poison-producing glands, the parotoids, produce the neurotoxin bufotoxin and are located behind the ears of toads, along the backs of frogs, behind the eyes of salamanders and on the upper surface of caecilians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The skin colour of amphibians is produced by three layers of pigment cells called chromatophores.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] These three cell layers consist of the melanophores (occupying the deepest layer), the guanophores (forming an intermediate layer and containing many granules, producing a blue-green colour) and the lipophores (yellow, the most superficial layer).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The colour change displayed by many species is initiated by hormones secreted by the pituitary gland.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Unlike bony fish, there is no direct control of the pigment cells by the nervous system, and this results in the colour change taking place more slowly than happens in fish.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] A vividly coloured skin usually indicates that the species is toxic and is a warning sign to predators.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Amphibians have a skeletal system that is structurally homologous to other tetrapods, though with a number of variations.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They all have four limbs except for the legless caecilians and a few species of salamander with reduced or no limbs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The musculoskeletal system is strong to enable it to support the head and body.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The bones are fully ossified and the vertebrae interlock with each other by means of overlapping processes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The pectoral girdle is supported by muscle, and the well-developed pelvic girdle is attached to the backbone by a pair of sacral ribs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The ilium slopes forward and the body is held closer to the ground than is the case in mammals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In most amphibians, there are four digits on the fore foot and five on the hind foot, but no claws on either.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Some salamanders have fewer digits and the amphiumas are eel-like in appearance with tiny, stubby legs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The sirens are aquatic salamanders with stumpy forelimbs and no hind limbs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They burrow in the manner of earthworms with zones of muscle contractions moving along the body.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] On the surface of the ground or in water they move by undulating their body from side to side.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In frogs, the hind legs are larger than the fore legs, especially so in those species that principally move by jumping or swimming.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In the walkers and runners the hind limbs are not so large, and the burrowers mostly have short limbs and broad bodies.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The feet have adaptations for the way of life, with webbing between the toes for swimming, broad adhesive toe pads for climbing, and keratinised tubercles on the hind feet for digging (frogs usually dig backwards into the soil).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In most salamanders, the limbs are short and more or less the same length and project at right angles from the body.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Locomotion on land is by walking and the tail often swings from side to side or is used as a prop, particularly when climbing.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In their normal gait, only one leg is advanced at a time in the manner adopted by their ancestors, the lobe-finned fish.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Some salamanders in the genus *Aneides* and certain plethodontids climb trees and have long limbs, large toepads and prehensile tails.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In aquatic salamanders and in frog tadpoles, the tail has dorsal and ventral fins and is moved from side to side as a means of propulsion.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Adult frogs do not have tails and caecilians have only very short ones.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Salamanders use their tails in defence and some are prepared to jettison them to save their lives in a process known as autotomy.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Certain species in the Plethodontidae have a weak zone at the base of the tail and use this strategy readily.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The tail often continues to twitch after separation which may distract the attacker and allow the salamander to escape.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Both tails and limbs can be regenerated.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Adult frogs are unable to regrow limbs but tadpoles can do so.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Amphibians have a juvenile stage and an adult stage, and the circulatory systems of the two are distinct.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In the juvenile (or tadpole) stage, the circulation is similar to that of a fish; the two-chambered heart pumps the blood through the gills where it is oxygenated, and is spread around the body and back to the heart in a single loop.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In the adult stage, amphibians (especially frogs) lose their gills and develop lungs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They have a heart that consists of a single ventricle and two atria.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] When the ventricle starts contracting, deoxygenated blood is pumped through the pulmonary artery to the lungs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Continued contraction then pumps oxygenated blood around the rest of the body.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Mixing of the two bloodstreams is minimized by the anatomy of the chambers.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The nervous system is basically the same as in other vertebrates, with a central brain, a spinal cord, and nerves throughout the body.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The amphibian brain is relatively simple but broadly the same structurally as in reptiles, birds and mammals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Their brains are elongated, except in caecilians, and contain the usual motor and sensory areas of tetrapods.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The pineal body, known to regulate sleep patterns in humans, is thought to produce the hormones involved in hibernation and aestivation in amphibians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Tadpoles retain the lateral line system of their ancestral fishes, but this is lost in terrestrial adult amphibians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Many aquatic salamanders and some caecilians possess electroreceptors called ampullary organs (completely absent in anurans), that allow them to locate objects around them when submerged in water.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] There is no external ear, but the large circular eardrum lies on the surface of the head just behind the eye.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] This vibrates and sound is transmitted through a single bone, the stapes, to the inner ear.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Only high-frequency sounds like mating calls are heard in this way, but low-frequency noises can be detected through another mechanism.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] There is a patch of specialized haircells, called *papilla amphibiorum*, in the inner ear capable of detecting deeper sounds.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Another feature, unique to frogs and salamanders, is the columella-operculum complex adjoining the auditory capsule which is involved in the transmission of both airborne and seismic signals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The ears of salamanders and caecilians are less highly developed than those of frogs as they do not normally communicate with each other through the medium of sound.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The eyes of tadpoles lack lids, but at metamorphosis, the cornea becomes more dome-shaped, the lens becomes flatter, and eyelids and associated glands and ducts develop.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The adult eyes are an improvement on invertebrate eyes and were a first step in the development of more advanced vertebrate eyes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They allow colour vision and depth of focus.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In the retinas are green rods, which are receptive to a wide range of wavelengths.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Many amphibians catch their prey by flicking out an elongated tongue with a sticky tip and drawing it back into the mouth before seizing the item with their jaws.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Some use inertial feeding to help them swallow the prey, repeatedly thrusting their head forward sharply causing the food to move backwards in their mouth by inertia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Most amphibians swallow their prey whole without much chewing so they possess voluminous stomachs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The short oesophagus is lined with cilia that help to move the food to the stomach and mucus produced by glands in the mouth and pharynx eases its passage.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The enzyme chitinase produced in the stomach helps digest the chitinous cuticle of arthropod prey.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Amphibians possess a pancreas, liver and gall bladder.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The liver is usually large with two lobes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Its size is determined by its function as a glycogen and fat storage unit, and may change with the seasons as these reserves are built or used up.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Adipose tissue is another important means of storing energy and this occurs in the abdomen (in internal structures called fat bodies), under the skin and, in some salamanders, in the tail.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] There are two kidneys located dorsally, near the roof of the body cavity.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Their job is to filter the blood of metabolic waste and transport the urine via ureters to the urinary bladder where it is stored before being passed out periodically through the cloacal vent.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Larvae and most aquatic adult amphibians excrete the nitrogen as ammonia in large quantities of dilute urine, while terrestrial species, with a greater need to conserve water, excrete the less toxic product urea.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Some tree frogs with limited access to water excrete most of their metabolic waste as uric acid.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Most aquatic and semi-aquatic amphibians have a membranous skin which allows them to absorb water directly through it.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Some semi-aquatic animals also have similarly permeable bladder membrane.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] As a result, they tend to have high rates of urine production to offset this high water intake, and have urine which is low in dissolved salts.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The urinary bladder assists such animals to retain salts.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Some aquatic amphibian such as *Xenopus* do not reabsorb water, to prevent excessive water influx.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] For land-dwelling amphibians, dehydration results in reduced urine output.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The amphibian bladder is usually highly distensible and among some land-dwelling species of frogs and salamanders may account for between 20% and 50% of their total body weight.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Urine flows from the kidneys through the ureters into the bladder and is periodically released from the bladder to the cloaca.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The lungs in amphibians are primitive compared to those of amniotes, possessing few internal septa and large alveoli, and consequently having a comparatively slow diffusion rate for oxygen entering the blood.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Ventilation is accomplished by buccal pumping.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Most amphibians, however, are able to exchange gases with the water or air via their skin.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] To enable sufficient cutaneous respiration, the surface of their highly vascularised skin must remain moist to allow the oxygen to diffuse at a sufficiently high rate.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Because oxygen concentration in the water increases at both low temperatures and high flow rates, aquatic amphibians in these situations can rely primarily on cutaneous respiration, as in the Titicaca water frog and the hellbender salamander.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In air, where oxygen is more concentrated, some small species can rely solely on cutaneous gas exchange, most famously the plethodontid salamanders, which have neither lungs nor gills.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Many aquatic salamanders and all tadpoles have gills in their larval stage, with some (such as the axolotl) retaining gills as aquatic adults.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] For the purpose of reproduction, most amphibians require fresh water although some lay their eggs on land and have developed various means of keeping them moist.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] *Fejervarya raja*) can inhabit brackish water, but there are no true marine amphibians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] There are reports, however, of particular amphibian populations unexpectedly invading marine waters.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Such was the case with the Black Sea invasion of the natural hybrid *Pelophylax esculentus* reported in 2010.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Several hundred frog species in adaptive radiations (e.g., *Eleutherodactylus*, the Pacific *Platymantis*, the Australo-Papuan microhylids, and many other tropical frogs), however, do not need any water for breeding in the wild.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They reproduce via direct development, an ecological and evolutionary adaptation that has allowed them to be completely independent from free-standing water.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Almost all of these frogs live in wet tropical rainforests and their eggs hatch directly into miniature versions of the adult, passing through the tadpole stage within the egg.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Reproductive success of many amphibians is dependent not only on the quantity of rainfall, but the seasonal timing.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In the tropics, many amphibians breed continuously or at any time of year.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In temperate regions, breeding is mostly seasonal, usually in the spring, and is triggered by increasing day length, rising temperatures or rainfall.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Experiments have shown the importance of temperature, but the trigger event, especially in arid regions, is often a storm.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In anurans, males usually arrive at the breeding sites before females and the vocal chorus they produce may stimulate ovulation in females and the endocrine activity of males that are not yet reproductively active.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In caecilians, fertilisation is internal, the male extruding an intromittent organ, the phallodeum, and inserting it into the female cloaca.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The paired Müllerian glands inside the male cloaca secrete a fluid which resembles that produced by mammalian prostate glands and which may transport and nourish the sperm.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Fertilisation probably takes place in the oviduct.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The majority of salamanders also engage in internal fertilisation.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In most of these, the male deposits a spermatophore, a small packet of sperm on top of a gelatinous cone, on the substrate either on land or in the water.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The female takes up the sperm packet by grasping it with the lips of the cloaca and pushing it into the vent.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The spermatozoa move to the spermatheca in the roof of the cloaca where they remain until ovulation which may be many months later.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Courtship rituals and methods of transfer of the spermatophore vary between species.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] In some, the spermatophore may be placed directly into the female cloaca while in others, the female may be guided to the spermatophore or restrained with an embrace called amplexus.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Certain primitive salamanders in the families Sirenidae, Hynobiidae and Cryptobranchidae practice external fertilisation in a similar manner to frogs, with the female laying the eggs in water and the male releasing sperm onto the egg mass.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] With a few exceptions, frogs use external fertilisation.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The male grasps the female tightly with his forelimbs either behind the arms or in front of the back legs, or in the case of *Epipedobates tricolor*, around the neck.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They remain in amplexus with their cloacae positioned close together while the female lays the eggs and the male covers them with sperm.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Roughened nuptial pads on the male's hands aid in retaining grip.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Often the male collects and retains the egg mass, forming a sort of basket with the hind feet.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] An exception is the granular poison frog (*Oophaga granulifera*) where the male and female place their cloacae in close proximity while facing in opposite directions and then release eggs and sperm simultaneously.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The tailed frog (*Ascaphus truei*) exhibits internal fertilisation.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The "tail" is only possessed by the male and is an extension of the cloaca and used to inseminate the female.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] This frog lives in fast-flowing streams and internal fertilisation prevents the sperm from being washed away before fertilisation occurs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The sperm may be retained in storage tubes attached to the oviduct until the following spring.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Most frogs can be classified as either prolonged or explosive breeders.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Typically, prolonged breeders congregate at a breeding site, the males usually arriving first, calling and setting up territories.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Other satellite males remain quietly nearby, waiting for their opportunity to take over a territory.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The females arrive sporadically, mate selection takes place and eggs are laid.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The females depart and territories may change hands.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] More females appear and in due course, the breeding season comes to an end.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Explosive breeders on the other hand are found where temporary pools appear in dry regions after rainfall.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] These frogs are typically fossorial species that emerge after heavy rains and congregate at a breeding site.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] They are attracted there by the calling of the first male to find a suitable place, perhaps a pool that forms in the same place each rainy season.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] The assembled frogs may call in unison and frenzied activity ensues, the males scrambling to mate with the usually smaller number of females.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] There is a direct competition between males to win the attention of the females in salamanders and newts, with elaborate courtship displays to keep the female's attention long enough to get her interested in choosing him to mate with.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Some species store sperm through long breeding seasons, as the extra time may allow for interactions with rival sperm.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Unisexual female mole salamanders (genus Ambystoma) are common in the Great Lakes region of North America.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] These salamanders are the oldest known unisexual vertebrate lineage, having emerged about 5 million years ago.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p01] Genome exchange can sometimes occur between the unisexual female Ambystoma and males from sympatric sexual species.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Most amphibians go through metamorphosis, a process of significant morphological change after birth.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In typical amphibian development, eggs are laid in water and larvae are adapted to an aquatic lifestyle.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Frogs, toads and salamanders all hatch from the egg as larvae with external gills.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Metamorphosis in amphibians is regulated by thyroxine concentration in the blood, which stimulates metamorphosis, and prolactin, which counteracts thyroxine's effect.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Specific events are dependent on threshold values for different tissues.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Because most embryonic development is outside the parental body, it is subject to many adaptations due to specific environmental circumstances.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] For this reason tadpoles can have horny ridges instead of teeth, whisker-like skin extensions or fins.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] They also make use of a sensory lateral line organ similar to that of fish.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] After metamorphosis, these organs become redundant and will be reabsorbed by controlled cell death, called apoptosis.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The variety of adaptations to specific environmental circumstances among amphibians is wide, with many discoveries still being made.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In the egg, the embryo is suspended in perivitelline fluid and surrounded by semi-permeable gelatinous capsules, with the yolk mass providing nutrients.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] As the larvae hatch, the capsules are dissolved by enzymes secreted from gland at the tip of the snout.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The eggs of some salamanders and frogs contain unicellular green algae.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] These penetrate the jelly envelope after the eggs are laid and may increase the supply of oxygen to the embryo through photosynthesis.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] They seem to both speed up the development of the larvae and reduce mortality.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In the wood frog (*Rana sylvatica*), the interior of the globular egg cluster has been found to be up to 6 °C (11 °F) warmer than its surroundings, which is an advantage in its cool northern habitat.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The eggs may be deposited singly, in cluster or in long strands.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Sites for laying eggs include water, mud, burrows, debris and on plants or under logs or stones.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The greenhouse frog (*Eleutherodactylus planirostris*) lays eggs in small groups in the soil where they develop in about two weeks directly into juvenile frogs without an intervening larval stage.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The tungara frog (*Physalaemus pustulosus*) builds a floating nest from foam to protect its eggs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] First a raft is built, then eggs are laid in the centre, and finally a foam cap is overlaid.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] It contains no detergents but is created by whipping up proteins and lectins secreted by the female.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The eggs of amphibians are typically laid in water and hatch into free-living larvae that complete their development in water and later transform into either aquatic or terrestrial adults.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In many species of frog and in most lungless salamanders (Plethodontidae), direct development takes place, the larvae growing within the eggs and emerging as miniature adults.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Many caecilians and some other amphibians lay their eggs on land, and the newly hatched larvae wriggle or are transported to water bodies.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Some caecilians, the alpine salamander (*Salamandra atra*) and some of the African live-bearing toads (*Nectophrynoides spp.*) are viviparous.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Their larvae feed on glandular secretions and develop within the female's oviduct, often for long periods.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Other amphibians, but not caecilians, are ovoviviparous.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The eggs are retained in or on the parent's body, but the larvae subsist on the yolks of their eggs and receive no nourishment from the adult.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The larvae emerge at varying stages of their growth, either before or after metamorphosis, according to their species.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The toad genus *Nectophrynoides* exhibits all of these developmental patterns among its dozen or so members.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] They have thick, rounded bodies with powerful muscular tails.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Unlike in other amphibians, frog tadpoles do not resemble adults.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The free-living larvae are normally fully aquatic, but the tadpoles of some species (such as *Nannophrys ceylonensis*) are semi-terrestrial and live among wet rocks.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Tadpoles have cartilaginous skeletons, gills for respiration (external gills at first, internal gills later), lateral line systems and large tails that they use for swimming.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Newly hatched tadpoles soon develop gill pouches that cover the gills.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] These internal gills and operculum are not homologous with those of fish, and are only found in tadpoles as both salamanders and caecilians have external gills only.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Combined with buccal pumping the internal gills has allowed tadpoles to adopt a filter feeding lifestyle, even if several species have since evolved other types of feeding strategies.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The lungs develop early and are used as accessory breathing organs, the tadpoles rising to the water surface to gulp air.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Some species complete their development inside the egg and hatch directly into small frogs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] These larvae do not have gills but instead have specialised areas of skin through which respiration takes place.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] While tadpoles do not have true teeth, in most species, the jaws have long, parallel rows of small keratinized structures called keradonts surrounded by a horny beak.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Front legs are formed under the gill sac and hind legs become visible a few days later.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In fact, tadpoles developing in ponds and streams are typically herbivorous.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Pond tadpoles tend to have deep bodies, large caudal fins and small mouths; they swim in the quiet waters feeding on growing or loose fragments of vegetation.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Stream dwellers mostly have larger mouths, shallow bodies and caudal fins; they attach themselves to plants and stones and feed on the surface films of algae and bacteria.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] They also feed on diatoms, filtered from the water through the gills, and stir up the sediment at bottom of the pond, ingesting edible fragments.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] They have a relatively long, spiral-shaped gut to enable them to digest this diet.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Some species are carnivorous at the tadpole stage, eating insects, smaller tadpoles and fish.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Young of the Cuban tree frog (*Osteopilus septentrionalis*) can occasionally be cannibalistic, the younger tadpoles attacking a larger, more developed tadpole when it is undergoing metamorphosis.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] At metamorphosis, rapid changes in the body take place as the lifestyle of the frog changes completely.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The spiral-shaped mouth with horny tooth ridges is reabsorbed together with the spiral gut.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The animal develops a large jaw, and its gills disappear along with its gill sac.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Eyes and legs grow quickly, and a tongue is formed.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] There are associated changes in the neural networks such as development of stereoscopic vision and loss of the lateral line system.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] A few days later, the tail is reabsorbed, due to the higher thyroxine concentration required for this to take place.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] At hatching, a typical salamander larva has eyes without lids, teeth in both upper and lower jaws, three pairs of feathery external gills, and a long tail with dorsal and ventral fins.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The forelimbs may be partially developed and the hind limbs are rudimentary in pond-living species but may be rather more developed in species that reproduce in moving water.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Pond-type larvae often have a pair of balancers, rod-like structures on either side of the head that may prevent the gills from becoming clogged up with sediment.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Some have larvae that never fully develop into the adult form, a condition known as neoteny.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Neoteny occurs when the animal's growth rate is very low and is usually linked to adverse conditions such as low water temperatures that may change the response of the tissues to the hormone thyroxine. as well as lack of food.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Lungless salamanders in the family Plethodontidae are terrestrial and lay a small number of unpigmented eggs in a cluster among damp leaf litter.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Each egg has a large yolk sac and the larva feeds on this while it develops inside the egg, emerging fully formed as a juvenile salamander.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The female salamander often broods the eggs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In the genus *Ensatinas*, the female has been observed to coil around them and press her throat area against them, effectively massaging them with a mucous secretion.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In newts and salamanders, metamorphosis is less dramatic than in frogs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] This is because the larvae are already carnivorous and continue to feed as predators when they are adults so few changes are needed to their digestive systems.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Their lungs are functional early, but the larvae do not make as much use of them as do tadpoles.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Their gills are never covered by gill sacs and are reabsorbed just before the animals leave the water.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Other changes include the reduction in size or loss of tail fins, the closure of gill slits, thickening of the skin, the development of eyelids, and certain changes in dentition and tongue structure.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Salamanders are at their most vulnerable at metamorphosis as swimming speeds are reduced and transforming tails are encumbrances on land.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Adult salamanders often have an aquatic phase in spring and summer, and a land phase in winter.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] For adaptation to a water phase, prolactin is the required hormone, and for adaptation to the land phase, thyroxine.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] External gills do not return in subsequent aquatic phases because these are completely absorbed upon leaving the water for the first time.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Most terrestrial caecilians that lay eggs do so in burrows or moist places on land near bodies of water.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The development of the young of *Ichthyophis glutinosus*, a species from Sri Lanka, has been much studied.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The eel-like larvae hatch out of the eggs and make their way to water.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] They have three pairs of external red feathery gills, a blunt head with two rudimentary eyes, a lateral line system and a short tail with fins.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] They swim by undulating their body from side to side.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] They are mostly active at night, soon lose their gills and make sorties onto land.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] By the age of about ten months they have developed a pointed head with sensory tentacles near the mouth and lost their eyes, lateral line systems and tails.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The skin thickens, embedded scales develop and the body divides into segments.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] By this time, the caecilian has constructed a burrow and is living on land.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In the majority of species of caecilians, the young are produced by viviparity.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] *Typhlonectes compressicauda*, a species from South America, is typical of these.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Up to nine larvae can develop in the oviduct at any one time.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] They are elongated and have paired sac-like gills, small eyes and specialised scraping teeth.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] At first, they feed on the yolks of the eggs, but as this source of nourishment declines they begin to rasp at the ciliated epithelial cells that line the oviduct.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] This stimulates the secretion of fluids rich in lipids and mucoproteins on which they feed along with scrapings from the oviduct wall.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] They may increase their length sixfold and be two-fifths as long as their mother before being born.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] By this time they have undergone metamorphosis, lost their eyes and gills, developed a thicker skin and mouth tentacles, and reabsorbed their teeth.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] A permanent set of teeth grow through soon after birth.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Gills are only necessarily during embryonic development, and in species that give birth the offspring is born after gill degeneration.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In egg laying caecilians the gills are either reabsorbed before hatching, or, in species that hatch with gill remnants still present, short lived and only leaves behind a gill slit.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] For species with scales under their skin, the scales does not form before during metamorphosis.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The ringed caecilian (*Siphonops annulatus*) has developed a unique adaptation for the purposes of reproduction.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The progeny feed on a skin layer that is specially developed by the adult in a phenomenon known as maternal dermatophagy.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The brood feed as a batch for about seven minutes at intervals of approximately three days which gives the skin an opportunity to regenerate.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Meanwhile, they have been observed to ingest fluid exuded from the maternal cloaca.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The care of offspring among amphibians has been little studied but, in general, the larger the number of eggs in a batch, the less likely it is that any degree of parental care takes place.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Nevertheless, it is estimated that in up to 20% of amphibian species, one or both adults play some role in the care of the young.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Those species that breed in smaller water bodies or other specialised habitats tend to have complex patterns of behaviour in the care of their young.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Many woodland salamanders lay clutches of eggs under dead logs or stones on land.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The black mountain salamander (*Desmognathus welteri*) does this, the mother brooding the eggs and guarding them from predation as the embryos feed on the yolks of their eggs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] When fully developed, they break their way out of the egg capsules and disperse as juvenile salamanders.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The male hellbender, a primitive salamander, excavates an underwater nest and encourages females to lay there.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The male then guards the site for the two or three months before the eggs hatch, using body undulations to fan the eggs and increase their supply of oxygen.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The male *Colostethus subpunctatus*, a tiny frog, protects the egg cluster which is hidden under a stone or log.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] When the eggs hatch, the male transports the tadpoles on his back, stuck there by a mucous secretion, to a temporary pool where he dips himself into the water and the tadpoles drop off.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The male midwife toad (*Alytes obstetricans*) winds egg strings round his thighs and carries the eggs around for up to eight weeks.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] He keeps them moist and when they are ready to hatch, he visits a pond or ditch and releases the tadpoles.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The female gastric-brooding frog (*Rheobatrachus spp.*) reared larvae in her stomach after swallowing either the eggs or hatchlings; however, this stage was never observed before the species became extinct.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The tadpoles secrete a hormone that inhibits digestion in the mother whilst they develop by consuming their very large yolk supply.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The pouched frog (*Assa darlingtoni*) lays eggs on the ground.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] When they hatch, the male carries the tadpoles around in brood pouches on his hind legs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The aquatic Surinam toad (*Pipa pipa*) raises its young in pores on its back where they remain until metamorphosis.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The granular poison frog (*Oophaga granulifera*) is typical of a number of tree frogs in the poison dart frog family Dendrobatidae.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Its eggs are laid on the forest floor and when they hatch, the tadpoles are carried one by one on the back of an adult to a suitable water-filled crevice such as the axil of a leaf or the rosette of a bromeliad.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The female visits the nursery sites regularly and deposits unfertilised eggs in the water and these are consumed by the tadpoles.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Amphibians are notable among vertebrates for their diversity of chromosomes and genomes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The karyotypes (chromosomes) have been determined for at least 1,193 (14.5%) of the ≈8,200 known (diploid) species, including 963 anurans, 209 salamanders, and 21 caecilians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Generally, the karyotypes of diploid amphibians are characterized by 20–26 bi-armed chromosomes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Amphibians have also very large genomes compared to other taxa of vertebrates and corresponding variation in genome size (C-value: picograms of DNA in haploid nuclei).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The genome sizes range from 0.95 to 11.5 pg in frogs, from 13.89 to 120.56 pg in salamanders, and from 2.94 to 11.78 pg in caecilians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The large genome sizes have prevented whole-genome sequencing of amphibians although a number of genomes have been published recently.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The 1.7GB draft genome of *Xenopus tropicalis* was the first to be reported for amphibians in 2010.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Compared to some salamanders this frog genome is tiny.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] For instance, the genome of the Mexican axolotl turned out to be 32 Gb, which is more than 10 times larger than the human genome (3GB).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] With a few exceptions, adult amphibians are predators, feeding on virtually anything that moves that they can swallow.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The diet mostly consists of small prey that do not move too fast such as beetles, caterpillars, earthworms and spiders.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The sirens (*Siren spp.*) often ingest aquatic plant material with the invertebrates on which they feed and a Brazilian tree frog (*Xenohyla truncata*) includes a large quantity of fruit in its diet.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The Mexican burrowing toad (*Rhinophrynus dorsalis*) has a specially adapted tongue for picking up ants and termites.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] It projects it with the tip foremost whereas other frogs flick out the rear part first, their tongues being hinged at the front.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Food is mostly selected by sight, even in conditions of dim light.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Movement of the prey triggers a feeding response.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Frogs have been caught on fish hooks baited with red flannel and green frogs (*Rana clamitans*) have been found with stomachs full of elm seeds that they had seen floating past.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Toads, salamanders and caecilians also use smell to detect prey.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] This response is mostly secondary because salamanders have been observed to remain stationary near odoriferous prey but only feed if it moves.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Cave-dwelling amphibians normally hunt by smell.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Some salamanders seem to have learned to recognize immobile prey when it has no smell, even in complete darkness.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Amphibians usually swallow food whole but may chew it lightly first to subdue it.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] They typically have small hinged pedicellate teeth, a feature unique to amphibians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The base and crown of these are composed of dentine separated by an uncalcified layer and they are replaced at intervals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Salamanders, caecilians and some frogs have one or two rows of teeth in both jaws, but some frogs (*Rana spp.*) lack teeth in the lower jaw, and toads (*Bufo spp.*) have no teeth.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In many amphibians there are also vomerine teeth attached to a facial bone in the roof of the mouth.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The tiger salamander (*Ambystoma tigrinum*) is typical of the frogs and salamanders that hide under cover ready to ambush unwary invertebrates.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Other amphibians, such as the *Bufo spp.* toads, actively search for prey, while the Argentine horned frog (*Ceratophrys ornata*) lures inquisitive prey closer by raising its hind feet over its back and vibrating its yellow toes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Among leaf litter frogs in Panama, frogs that actively hunt prey have narrow mouths and are slim, often brightly coloured and toxic, while ambushers have wide mouths and are broad and well-camouflaged.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Caecilians do not flick their tongues, but catch their prey by grabbing it with their slightly backward-pointing teeth.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The struggles of the prey and further jaw movements work it inwards and the caecilian usually retreats into its burrow.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] When they are newly hatched, frog larvae feed on the yolk of the egg.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] When this is exhausted some move on to feed on bacteria, algal crusts, detritus and raspings from submerged plants.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Water is drawn in through their mouths, which are usually at the bottom of their heads, and passes through branchial food traps between their mouths and their gills where fine particles are trapped in mucus and filtered out.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Others have specialised mouthparts consisting of a horny beak edged by several rows of labial teeth.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] They scrape and bite food of many kinds as well as stirring up the bottom sediment, filtering out larger particles with the papillae around their mouths.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Some, such as the spadefoot toads, have strong biting jaws and are carnivorous or even cannibalistic.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The calls made by caecilians and salamanders are limited to occasional soft squeaks, grunts or hisses and have not been much studied.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] A clicking sound sometimes produced by caecilians may be a means of orientation, as in bats, or a form of communication.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Most salamanders are considered voiceless, but the California giant salamander (*Dicamptodon ensatus*) has vocal cords and can produce a rattling or barking sound.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Some species of salamander emit a quiet squeak or yelp if attacked.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Frogs are much more vocal, especially during the breeding season when they use their voices to attract mates.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The presence of a particular species in an area may be more easily discerned by its characteristic call than by a fleeting glimpse of the animal itself.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In most species, the sound is produced by expelling air from the lungs over the vocal cords into one or more air sacs in the throat or at the corner of the mouth.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] This may distend like a balloon and acts as a resonator, helping to transfer the sound to the atmosphere, or the water at times when the animal is submerged.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The main vocalisation is the male's loud advertisement call which seeks to both encourage a female to approach and discourage other males from intruding on its territory.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] This call is modified to a quieter courtship call on the approach of a female or to a more aggressive version if a male intruder draws near.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Calling carries the risk of attracting predators and involves the expenditure of much energy.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Other calls include those given by a female in response to the advertisement call and a release call given by a male or female during unwanted attempts at amplexus.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] When a frog is attacked, a distress or fright call is emitted, often resembling a scream.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The usually nocturnal Cuban tree frog (*Osteopilus septentrionalis*) produces a rain call when there is rainfall during daylight hours.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Little is known of the territorial behaviour of caecilians, but some frogs and salamanders defend home ranges.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] These are usually feeding, breeding or sheltering sites.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Males normally exhibit such behaviour though in some species, females and even juveniles are also involved.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Although in many frog species, females are larger than males, this is not the case in most species where males are actively involved in territorial defence.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Some of these have specific adaptations such as enlarged teeth for biting or spines on the chest, arms or thumbs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In salamanders, defence of a territory involves adopting an aggressive posture and if necessary attacking the intruder.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] This may involve snapping, chasing and sometimes biting, occasionally causing the loss of a tail.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The behaviour of red back salamanders (*Plethodon cinereus*) has been much studied.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] 91% of marked individuals that were later recaptured were within a metre (yard) of their original daytime retreat under a log or rock.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] A similar proportion, when moved experimentally a distance of 30 metres (98 ft), found their way back to their home base.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The salamanders left odour marks around their territories which averaged 0.16 to 0.33 square metres (1.7 to 3.6 sq ft) in size and were sometimes inhabited by a male and female pair.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] These deterred the intrusion of others and delineated the boundaries between neighbouring areas.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Much of their behaviour seemed stereotyped and did not involve any actual contact between individuals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] An aggressive posture involved raising the body off the ground and glaring at the opponent who often turned away submissively.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] If the intruder persisted, a biting lunge was usually launched at either the tail region or the naso-labial grooves.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Damage to either of these areas can reduce the fitness of the rival, either because of the need to regenerate tissue or because it impairs its ability to detect food.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In frogs, male territorial behaviour is often observed at breeding locations; calling is both an announcement of ownership of part of this resource and an advertisement call to potential mates.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In general, a deeper voice represents a heavier and more powerful individual, and this may be sufficient to prevent intrusion by smaller males.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Much energy is used in the vocalization and it takes a toll on the territory holder who may be displaced by a fitter rival if he tires.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] There is a tendency for males to tolerate the holders of neighbouring territories while vigorously attacking unknown intruders.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Holders of territories have a "home advantage" and usually come off better in an encounter between two similar-sized frogs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] If threats are insufficient, chest to chest tussles may take place.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Fighting methods include pushing and shoving, deflating the opponent's vocal sac, seizing him by the head, jumping on his back, biting, chasing, splashing, and ducking him under the water.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Amphibians have soft bodies with thin skins, and lack claws, defensive armour, or spines.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Nevertheless, they have evolved various defence mechanisms to keep themselves alive.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The first line of defence in salamanders and frogs is the mucous secretion that they produce.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] This keeps their skin moist and makes them slippery and difficult to grip.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The secretion is often sticky and distasteful or toxic.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Snakes have been observed yawning and gaping when trying to swallow African clawed frogs (*Xenopus laevis*), which gives the frogs an opportunity to escape.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Caecilians have been little studied in this respect, but the Cayenne caecilian (*Typhlonectes compressicauda*) produces toxic mucus that has killed predatory fish in a feeding experiment in Brazil.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In some salamanders, the skin is poisonous.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The rough-skinned newt (*Taricha granulosa*) from North America and other members of its genus contain the neurotoxin tetrodotoxin (TTX), the most toxic non-protein substance known and almost identical to that produced by pufferfish.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Handling the newts does not cause harm, but ingestion of even the most minute amounts of the skin is deadly.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In feeding trials, fish, frogs, reptiles, birds and mammals were all found to be susceptible.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The only predators with some tolerance to the poison are certain populations of common garter snake (*Thamnophis sirtalis*).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In locations where both snake and salamander co-exist, the snakes have developed immunity through genetic changes and they feed on the amphibians with impunity.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Coevolution occurs with the newt increasing its toxic capabilities at the same rate as the snake further develops its immunity.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Some frogs and toads are toxic, the main poison glands being at the side of the neck and under the warts on the back.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] These regions are presented to the attacking animal and their secretions may be foul-tasting or cause various physical or neurological symptoms.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Altogether, over 200 toxins have been isolated from the limited number of amphibian species that have been investigated.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Poisonous species often use bright colouring to warn potential predators of their toxicity.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] These warning colours tend to be red or yellow combined with black, with the fire salamander (*Salamandra salamandra*) being an example.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Once a predator has sampled one of these, it is likely to remember the colouration next time it encounters a similar animal.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In some species, such as the fire-bellied toad (*Bombina spp.*), the warning colouration is on the belly and these animals adopt a defensive pose when attacked, exhibiting their bright colours to the predator.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The frog *Allobates zaparo* is not poisonous, but mimics the appearance of other toxic species in its locality, a strategy that may deceive predators.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Many amphibians are nocturnal and hide during the day, thereby avoiding diurnal predators that hunt by sight.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Other amphibians use camouflage to avoid being detected.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] They have various colourings such as mottled browns, greys and olives to blend into the background.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Some salamanders adopt defensive poses when faced by a potential predator such as the North American northern short-tailed shrew (*Blarina brevicauda*).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Their bodies writhe and they raise and lash their tails which makes it difficult for the predator to avoid contact with their poison-producing granular glands.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] A few salamanders will autotomise their tails when attacked, sacrificing this part of their anatomy to enable them to escape.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The tail may have a constriction at its base to allow it to be easily detached.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The tail is regenerated later, but the energy cost to the animal of replacing it is significant.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Some frogs and toads inflate themselves to make themselves look large and fierce, and some spadefoot toads (*Pelobates spp*) scream and leap towards the attacker.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Giant salamanders of the genus *Andrias*, as well as Ceratophrine and *Pyxicephalus* frogs possess sharp teeth and are capable of drawing blood with a defensive bite.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The blackbelly salamander (*Desmognathus quadramaculatus*) can bite an attacking common garter snake (*Thamnophis sirtalis*) two or three times its size on the head and often manages to escape.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In amphibians, there is evidence of habituation, associative learning through both classical and instrumental learning, and discrimination abilities.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Amphibians are widely considered to be sentient, able to feel emotions such as anxiety and fear.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In one experiment, when offered live fruit flies (*Drosophila virilis*), salamanders chose the larger of 1 vs 2 and 2 vs 3.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Frogs can distinguish between low numbers (1 vs 2, 2 vs 3, but not 3 vs 4) and large numbers (3 vs 6, 4 vs 8, but not 4 vs 6) of prey.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] This is irrespective of other characteristics, i.e. surface area, volume, weight and movement, although discrimination among large numbers may be based on surface area.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Dramatic declines in amphibian populations, including population crashes and mass localized extinction, have been noted since the late 1980s from locations all over the world, and amphibian declines are thus perceived to be one of the most critical threats to global biodiversity.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In 2004, the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) reported stating that currently birds, mammals, and amphibians extinction rates were at minimum 48 times greater than natural extinction rates—possibly 1,024 times higher.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In 2006, there were believed to be 4,035 species of amphibians that depended on water at some stage during their life cycle.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Of these, 1,356 (33.6%) were considered to be threatened and this figure is likely to be an underestimate because it excludes 1,427 species for which there was insufficient data to assess their status.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] However, many of the causes of amphibian declines are still poorly understood, and are a topic of ongoing discussion.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Any decline in amphibian numbers will affect the patterns of predation.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The loss of carnivorous species near the top of the food chain will upset the delicate ecosystem balance and may cause dramatic increases in opportunistic species.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Predators that feed on amphibians are affected by their decline.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The western terrestrial garter snake (*Thamnophis elegans*) in California is largely aquatic and depends heavily on two species of frog that are decreasing in numbers, the Yosemite toad (*Bufo canorus*) and the mountain yellow-legged frog (*Rana muscosa*), putting the snake's future at risk.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] If the snake were to become scarce, this would affect birds of prey and other predators that feed on it.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Meanwhile, in the ponds and lakes, fewer frogs means fewer tadpoles.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] These normally play an important role in controlling the growth of algae and also forage on detritus that accumulates as sediment on the bottom.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] A reduction in the number of tadpoles may lead to an overgrowth of algae, resulting in depletion of oxygen in the water when the algae later die and decompose.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Aquatic invertebrates and fish might then die and there would be unpredictable ecological consequences.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The decline in amphibian and reptile populations has led to an awareness of the effects of pesticides on reptiles and amphibians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In the past, the argument that amphibians or reptiles were more susceptible to any chemical contamination than any land aquatic vertebrate was not supported by research until recently.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Amphibians and reptiles have complex life cycles, live in different climate and ecological zones, and are more vulnerable to chemical exposure.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Certain pesticides, such as organophosphates, neonicotinoids, and carbamates, react via cholinesterase inhibition.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Cholinesterase is an enzyme that causes the hydrolysis of acetylcholine, an excitatory neurotransmitter that is abundant in the nervous system.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] AChE inhibitors are either reversible or irreversible, and carbamates are safer than organophosphorus insecticides, which are more likely to cause cholinergic poisoning.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Reptile exposure to an AChE inhibitory pesticide may result in disruption of neural function in reptiles.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The buildup of these inhibitory effects on motor performance, such as food consumption and other activities.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] The Amphibian Specialist Group of the IUCN is spearheading efforts to implement a comprehensive global strategy for amphibian conservation.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Amphibian Ark is an organization that was formed to implement the ex-situ conservation recommendations of this plan, and they have been working with zoos and aquaria around the world, encouraging them to create assurance colonies of threatened amphibians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] One such project is the Panama Amphibian Rescue and Conservation Project that built on existing conservation efforts in Panama to create a country-wide response to the threat of chytridiomycosis.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] Another measure would be to stop exploitation of frogs for human consumption.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-p02] In the Middle East, a growing appetite for eating frog legs and the consequent gathering of them for food was already linked to an increase in mosquitoes and thus has direct consequences for human health.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] The American Museum of Natural History hosts *Amphibian Species of the World*, which is updated by herpetologist Darrel Frost.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] As of 2024, it contained more than 8700 species.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] The Association of Systematics Collections (ASC) started this project in 1978 because the Convention on Trade in Endangered Species of Fauna and Flora (CITES) needed a database for animals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] (The ASC later changed its name to Natural Science Collections Alliance.) The ASC's Stephen R.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] Edwards wrote *Mammal Species of the World* first and started *Amphibian Species of the World* second.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] Edwards decided to write about living amphibians because Richard G.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] Zweifel had just composed a large list of amphibian names and because experts from the University of Kansas were available to assist him.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] Darrel Frost joined the project to help Edwards.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] Frost planned to write *Turtle and Crocodilian Species of the World* next, but he left to complete his Ph.D. instead.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] The first version of the catalogue was published as a book in 1985, and well received by specialists in the field.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] In 1989, the ASC gave the copyright for *Amphibian Species of the World* to the Herpetologists' League, and they added more amphibians to the database.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] The League and American Museum of Natural History put Darrel Frost in charge of the project.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] At the time, Frost was a curator at the American Museum of Natural History.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] Frost added more information for professional herpetologists to use and made many corrections.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] He added more species that had been discovered since 1985.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] The project's own page notes that there are ten times as many amphibian species known to science today than were known in the mid-1980s.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] In July 1999, the catalogue was first published on the internet, in its 2.0 version.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] The 6.0 version, published in 2014, allows for real-time modifications.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] The 6.2 version was published in January 2023.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] As of August, the website contains 8,674 species and over 17,848 references.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibian-species-of-the-world] According to Amphibians.org, "For three decades ASW has been the primary reference for amphibian taxonomy." In 2013, Frost won the Sabin Award for his work on *Amphibian Species of the World*.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibiaweb] AmphibiaWeb's goal is to provide a single page for every species of amphibian in the world so research scientists, citizen scientists and conservationists can collaborate.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibiaweb] It added its 7000th animal in 2012, a glass frog from Peru.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibiaweb] As of 2022, it hosted more than 8,400 species located worldwide.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibiaweb] Scientist David Wake founded AmphibiaWeb in 2000.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibiaweb] Wake had been inspired by the decline of amphibian populations across the world.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibiaweb] He founded it at the Digital Library Project at the University of California at Berkeley in 2000.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibiaweb] Wake came to consider AmphibiaWeb part of his legacy.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/amphibiaweb] AmphibiaWeb provides information to the IUCN, CalPhotos, Encyclopedia of Life and iNaturalist, and the database is cited in scientific publications.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/andinobates-cassidyhornae] This species is threatened due to disturbance within its preferred habitat and small range and potential smuggling by the illegal pet trade.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/andinobates-cassidyhornae] It was proposed as critically endangered upon discovery, and is currently listed as vulnerable by the IUCN Red List.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The animal kingdom is divided into five major clades, namely Porifera, Ctenophora, Placozoa, Cnidaria and Bilateria.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The much smaller basal phylum Xenacoelomorpha have an uncertain position within Bilateria.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals first appeared in the fossil record in the late Cryogenian period and diversified in the subsequent Ediacaran period in what is known as the Avalon explosion.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Nearly all modern animal phyla first appeared in the fossil record as marine species during the Cambrian explosion, which began around 539 million years ago (Mya), and most classes during the Ordovician radiation 485.4 Mya.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Common to all living animals, 6,331 groups of genes have been identified that may have arisen from a single common ancestor that lived about 650 Mya during the Cryogenian period.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Historically, Aristotle divided animals into those with blood and those without.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical biological classification for animals in 1758 with his *Systema Naturae*, which Jean-Baptiste Lamarck expanded into 14 phyla by 1809.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into the multicellular **Metazoa** (now synonymous with Animalia) and the Protozoa, single-celled organisms no longer considered animals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In modern times, the biological classification of animals relies on advanced techniques, such as molecular phylogenetics, which are effective at demonstrating the evolutionary relationships between taxa.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Humans make use of many other animal species for food (including meat, eggs, and dairy products), for materials (such as leather, fur, and wool), as pets and as working animals for transportation, and services.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Dogs, the first domesticated animal, have been used in hunting, in security and in warfare, as have horses, pigeons and birds of prey; while other terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sports, trophies or profits.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Non-human animals are also an important cultural element of human evolution, having appeared in cave arts and totems since the earliest times, and are frequently featured in mythology, religion, arts, literature, heraldry, politics, and sports.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The word *animal* comes from the Latin noun *animal* of the same meaning, which is itself derived from Latin *animalis* 'having breath or soul'.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The biological definition includes all members of the kingdom Animalia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In colloquial usage, the term *animal* is often used to refer only to nonhuman animals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The term *metazoa* is derived from Ancient Greek μετα *meta* 'after' (in biology, the prefix *meta-* stands for 'later') and ζῷᾰ *zōia* 'animals', plural of ζῷον *zōion* 'animal'.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] A **metazoan** is any member of the group *Metazoa*.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals have several characteristics that they share with other living things.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals are eukaryotic, multicellular, and aerobic, as are plants and fungi.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Unlike plants and algae, which produce their own food, animals cannot produce their own food, a feature they share with fungi.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals ingest organic material and digest it internally.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Typically, there is an internal digestive chamber with either one opening (in Ctenophora, Cnidaria, and flatworms) or two openings (in most bilaterians).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animal development is controlled by Hox genes, which signal the times and places to develop structures such as body segments and limbs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] During development, the animal extracellular matrix forms a relatively flexible framework upon which cells can move about and be reorganised into specialised tissues and organs, making the formation of complex structures possible, and allowing cells to be differentiated.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The extracellular matrix may be calcified, forming structures such as shells, bones, and spicules.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In contrast, the cells of other multicellular organisms (primarily algae, plants, and fungi) are held in place by cell walls, and so develop by progressive growth.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Nearly all animals make use of some form of sexual reproduction.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] They produce haploid gametes by meiosis; the smaller, motile gametes are spermatozoa and the larger, non-motile gametes are ova.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] These fuse to form zygotes, which develop via mitosis into a hollow sphere, called a blastula.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In sponges, blastula larvae swim to a new location, attach to the seabed, and develop into a new sponge.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In most other groups, the blastula undergoes more complicated rearrangement.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] It first invaginates to form a gastrula with a digestive chamber and two separate germ layers, an external ectoderm and an internal endoderm.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In most cases, a third germ layer, the mesoderm, also develops between them.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] These germ layers then differentiate to form tissues and organs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Repeated instances of mating with a close relative during sexual reproduction generally leads to inbreeding depression within a population due to the increased prevalence of harmful recessive traits.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals have evolved numerous mechanisms for avoiding close inbreeding.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Some animals are capable of asexual reproduction, which often results in a genetic clone of the parent.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] This may take place through fragmentation; budding, such as in *Hydra* and other cnidarians; or parthenogenesis, where fertile eggs are produced without mating, such as in aphids.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals are categorised into ecological groups depending on their trophic levels and how they consume organic material.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Such groupings include carnivores (further divided into subcategories such as piscivores, insectivores, ovivores, etc.), herbivores (subcategorised into folivores, graminivores, frugivores, granivores, nectarivores, algivores, etc.), omnivores, fungivores, scavengers/detritivores, and parasites.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Interactions between animals of each biome form complex food webs within that ecosystem.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In carnivorous or omnivorous species, predation is a consumer–resource interaction where the predator feeds on another organism, its prey, who often evolves anti-predator adaptations to avoid being fed upon.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Selective pressures imposed on one another lead to an evolutionary arms race between predator and prey, resulting in various antagonistic/competitive coevolutions.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Almost all multicellular predators are animals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Some consumers use multiple methods; for example, in parasitoid wasps, the larvae feed on the hosts' living tissues, killing them in the process, but the adults primarily consume nectar from flowers.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Other animals may have very specific feeding behaviours, such as hawksbill sea turtles which mainly eat sponges.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Most animals rely on biomass and bioenergy produced by plants and phytoplanktons (collectively called producers) through photosynthesis.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Herbivores, as primary consumers, eat the plant material directly to digest and absorb the nutrients, while carnivores and other animals on higher trophic levels indirectly acquire the nutrients by eating the herbivores or other animals that have eaten the herbivores.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals oxidise carbohydrates, lipids, proteins and other biomolecules in cellular respiration, which allows the animal to grow and to sustain basal metabolism and fuel other biological processes such as locomotion.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Some benthic animals living close to hydrothermal vents and cold seeps on the dark sea floor consume organic matter produced through chemosynthesis (via oxidising inorganic compounds such as hydrogen sulfide) by archaea and bacteria.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals originated in the ocean; all extant animal phyla, except for Micrognathozoa and Onychophora, feature at least some marine species.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] However, several lineages of arthropods begun to colonise land around the same time as land plants, between 510 and 471 million years ago, during the Late Cambrian or Early Ordovician periods.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Vertebrates such as the lobe-finned fish *Tiktaalik* started to move on to land in the late Devonian, about 375 million years ago.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Other notable animal groups that colonized land environments are Mollusca, Platyhelmintha, Annelida, Tardigrada, Onychophora, Rotifera, Nematoda.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals occupy virtually all of earth's habitats and microhabitats, with faunas adapted to salt water, hydrothermal vents, fresh water, hot springs, swamps, forests, pastures, deserts, air, and the interiors of other organisms.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals are however not particularly heat tolerant; very few of them can survive at constant temperatures above 50 °C (122 °F) or in the most extreme cold deserts of continental Antarctica.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The collective global geomorphic influence of animals on the processes shaping the Earth's surface remains largely understudied, with most studies limited to individual species and well-known exemplars.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The blue whale (*Balaenoptera musculus*) is the largest animal that has ever lived, weighing up to 190 tonnes and measuring up to 33.6 metres (110 ft) long.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The largest extant terrestrial animal is the African bush elephant (*Loxodonta africana*), weighing up to 12.25 tonnes and measuring up to 10.67 metres (35.0 ft) long.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The largest terrestrial animals that ever lived were titanosaur sauropod dinosaurs such as *Argentinosaurus*, which may have weighed as much as 73 tonnes, and *Supersaurus* which may have reached 39 metres.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Several animals are microscopic; some Myxozoa (obligate parasites within the Cnidaria) never grow larger than 20 μm, and one of the smallest species (*Myxobolus shekel*) is no more than 8.5 μm when fully grown.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The following table lists estimated numbers of described extant species for the major animal phyla, along with their principal habitats (terrestrial, fresh water, and marine), and free-living or parasitic ways of life.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Species estimates shown here are based on numbers described scientifically; much larger estimates have been calculated based on various means of prediction, and these can vary wildly.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] For instance, around 25,000–27,000 species of nematodes have been described, while published estimates of the total number of nematode species include 10,000–20,000; 500,000; 10 million; and 100 million.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Using patterns within the taxonomic hierarchy, the total number of animal species—including those not yet described—was calculated to be about 7.77 million in 2011.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Evidence of animals is found as long ago as the Cryogenian period.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] 24-Isopropylcholestane (24-ipc) has been found in rocks from roughly 650 million years ago; it is only produced by sponges and pelagophyte algae.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Its likely origin is from sponges based on molecular clock estimates for the origin of 24-ipc production in both groups.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Analyses of pelagophyte algae consistently recover a Phanerozoic origin, while analyses of sponges recover a Neoproterozoic origin, consistent with the appearance of 24-ipc in the fossil record.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The first body fossils of animals appear in the Ediacaran, represented by forms such as *Charnia* and *Spriggina*.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] It had long been doubted whether these fossils truly represented animals, but the discovery of the animal lipid cholesterol in fossils of *Dickinsonia* establishes their nature.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals are thought to have originated under low-oxygen conditions, suggesting that they were capable of living entirely by anaerobic respiration, but as they became specialised for aerobic metabolism they became fully dependent on oxygen in their environments.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Many animal phyla first appear in the fossil record during the Cambrian explosion, starting about 539 million years ago, in beds such as the Burgess Shale.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Extant phyla in these rocks include molluscs, brachiopods, onychophorans, tardigrades, arthropods, echinoderms and hemichordates, along with numerous now-extinct forms such as the predatory *Anomalocaris*.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The apparent suddenness of the event may however be an artefact of the fossil record, rather than showing that all these animals appeared simultaneously.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] That view is supported by the discovery of *Auroralumina attenboroughii*, the earliest known Ediacaran crown-group cnidarian (557–562 mya, some 20 million years before the Cambrian explosion) from Charnwood Forest, England.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] It is thought to be one of the earliest predators, catching small prey with its nematocysts as modern cnidarians do.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Some palaeontologists have suggested that animals appeared much earlier than the Cambrian explosion, possibly as early as 1 billion years ago.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Early fossils that might represent animals appear for example in the 665-million-year-old rocks of the Trezona Formation of South Australia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] These fossils are interpreted as most probably being early sponges.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Trace fossils such as tracks and burrows found in the Tonian period (from 1 gya) may indicate the presence of triploblastic worm-like animals, roughly as large (about 5 mm wide) and complex as earthworms.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] However, similar tracks are produced by the giant single-celled protist *Gromia sphaerica*, so the Tonian trace fossils may not indicate early animal evolution.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Around the same time, the layered mats of microorganisms called stromatolites decreased in diversity, perhaps due to grazing by newly evolved animals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Objects such as sediment-filled tubes that resemble trace fossils of the burrows of wormlike animals have been found in 1.2 gya rocks in North America, in 1.5 gya rocks in Australia and North America, and in 1.7 gya rocks in Australia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Their interpretation as having an animal origin is disputed, as they might be water-escape or other structures.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals are monophyletic, meaning they are derived from a common ancestor.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals are the sister group to the choanoflagellates, with which they form the Choanozoa.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Ros-Rocher and colleagues (2021) trace the origins of animals to unicellular ancestors, providing the external phylogeny shown in the cladogram.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Uncertainty of relationships is indicated with dashed lines.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The animal clade had certainly originated by 650 mya, and may have come into being as much as 800 mya, based on molecular clock evidence for different phyla.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The relationships at the base of the animal tree have been debated.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Other than Ctenophora, the Bilateria and Cnidaria are the only groups with symmetry, and other evidence shows they are closely related.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In addition to sponges, Placozoa has no symmetry and was often considered a "missing link" between protists and multicellular animals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The presence of hox genes in Placozoa shows that they were once more complex.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The Porifera (sponges) have long been assumed to be sister to the rest of the animals, but there is evidence that the Ctenophora may be in that position.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Molecular phylogenetics has supported both the sponge-sister and ctenophore-sister hypotheses.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Sponges are physically very distinct from other animals, and were long thought to have diverged first, representing the oldest animal phylum and forming a sister clade to all other animals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Despite their morphological dissimilarity with all other animals, genetic evidence suggests sponges may be more closely related to other animals than the comb jellies are.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Sponges lack the complex organisation found in most other animal phyla; their cells are differentiated, but in most cases not organised into distinct tissues, unlike all other animals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Sponges are almost entirely sessile in their adult stage.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Sponges lack a digestive, circulatory, respiratory, or excretory system.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Instead, they rely on the flow of water through their bodies to perform these functions.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Many have adapted a hollow structure to facilitate the flow of water through their bodies.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] They typically feed by drawing in water through pores, filtering out small particles of food.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] They absorb oxygen dissolved in water, and they release carbon dioxide and nitrogenous waste into water that flows through them.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Sponges can reproduce sexually and asexually.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Asexual reproduction happens through a variety of mechanisms including by fragmentation, where a piece of the sponge splits off and reestablishes somewhere else.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] For sexual reproduction, most sponges are hermaphrodites, they produce both egg and sperm cells.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Comb jellies, members of Ctenophora, are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Ctenophora have distinct tissues, but these are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] They move using large arrays of cilia, called swimming plates.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] They have are unique in having colloblasts, structures on their tentacles that help them catch prey.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] They have nerve cells, but lack a brain or central nervous system.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Instead their nerves are arranged into a nerve net.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Their nerves are very different from those of other animals, and evidence suggests that their nerves developed independently of the nerves of other animals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Like Ctenophora, Cnidaria are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] They also have distinct tissues that are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Members of the group Anthozoa, such as sea anemones, coral, and sea pens only are sessile polyps.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Most members of Medusozoa, including jellyfish and most hydrozoans, have a polyp form as well, but also have a motile medusae stage.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The medusae stage are commonly known as jellyfish.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Cnidaria are diploblastic, having only two main germ layers, ectoderm and endoderm.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The tiny placozoans have no permanent digestive chamber and no symmetry; they superficially resemble amoebae.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Their phylogeny is poorly defined, and under active research.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The remaining animals, the great majority—comprising some 29 phyla and over a million species—form the Bilateria clade, which have a bilaterally symmetric body plan.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The Bilateria are triploblastic, with three well-developed germ layers, and their tissues form distinct organs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The digestive chamber has two openings, a mouth and an anus, and in the Nephrozoa there is an internal body cavity, a coelom or pseudocoelom.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] These animals have a head end (anterior) and a tail end (posterior), a back (dorsal) surface and a belly (ventral) surface, and a left and a right side.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] A modern consensus phylogenetic tree for the Bilateria is shown below.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Having a front end means that this part of the body encounters stimuli, such as food, favouring cephalisation, the development of a head with sense organs and a mouth.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Many bilaterians have a combination of circular muscles that constrict the body, making it longer, and an opposing set of longitudinal muscles, that shorten the body; these enable soft-bodied animals with a hydrostatic skeleton to move by peristalsis.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] They also have a gut that extends through the basically cylindrical body from mouth to anus.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Many bilaterian phyla have primary larvae which swim with cilia and have an apical organ containing sensory cells.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] However, over evolutionary time, descendant spaces have evolved which have lost one or more of each of these characteristics.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] For example, adult echinoderms are radially symmetric (unlike their larvae), while some parasitic worms have extremely simplified body structures.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Genetic studies have considerably changed zoologists' understanding of the relationships within the Bilateria.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Most appear to belong to two major lineages, the protostomes and the deuterostomes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] It is often suggested that the basalmost bilaterians are the Xenacoelomorpha, with all other bilaterians belonging to the subclade Nephrozoa.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] However, this suggestion has been contested, with other studies finding that xenacoelomorphs are more closely related to Ambulacraria than to other bilaterians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Protostomes and deuterostomes differ in several ways.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Early in development, deuterostome embryos undergo radial cleavage during cell division, while many protostomes (the Spiralia) undergo spiral cleavage.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals from both groups possess a complete digestive tract, but in protostomes the first opening of the embryonic gut develops into the mouth, and the anus forms secondarily.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In deuterostomes, the anus forms first while the mouth develops secondarily.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Most protostomes have schizocoelous development, where cells simply fill in the interior of the gastrula to form the mesoderm.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In deuterostomes, the mesoderm forms by enterocoelic pouching, through invagination of the endoderm.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The main deuterostome taxa are the Ambulacraria and the Chordata.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Ambulacraria are exclusively marine and include acorn worms, starfish, sea urchins, and sea cucumbers.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The chordates are dominated by the vertebrates (animals with backbones), which consist of fishes, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The protostomes include the Ecdysozoa, named after their shared trait of ecdysis, growth by moulting, Among the largest ecdysozoan phyla are the arthropods and the nematodes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The rest of the protostomes are in the Spiralia, named for their pattern of developing by spiral cleavage in the early embryo.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Major spiralian phyla include the annelids and molluscs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In the classical era, Aristotle divided animals, based on his own observations, into those with blood (roughly, the vertebrates) and those without.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In 1758, Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical classification in his *Systema Naturae*.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In his original scheme, the animals were one of three kingdoms, divided into the classes of Vermes, Insecta, Pisces, Amphibia, Aves, and Mammalia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Since then, the last four have all been subsumed into a single phylum, the Chordata, while his Insecta (which included the crustaceans and arachnids) and Vermes have been renamed or broken up.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The process was begun in 1793 by Jean-Baptiste de Lamarck, who called the Vermes *une espèce de chaos* ('a chaotic mess') and split the group into three new phyla: worms, echinoderms, and polyps (which contained corals and jellyfish).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] By 1809, in his *Philosophie Zoologique*, Lamarck had created nine phyla apart from vertebrates (where he still had four phyla: mammals, birds, reptiles, and fish) and molluscs, namely cirripedes, annelids, crustaceans, arachnids, insects, worms, radiates, polyps, and infusorians.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] This division into four was followed by the embryologist Karl Ernst von Baer in 1828, the zoologist Louis Agassiz in 1857, and the comparative anatomist Richard Owen in 1860.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into two subkingdoms: Metazoa (multicellular animals, with five phyla: coelenterates, echinoderms, articulates, molluscs, and vertebrates) and Protozoa (single-celled animals), including a sixth animal phylum, sponges.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The protozoa were later moved to the former kingdom Protista, leaving only the Metazoa as a synonym of Animalia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The human population exploits a large number of other animal species for food, both of domesticated livestock species in animal husbandry and, mainly at sea, by hunting wild species.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Marine fish of many species are caught commercially for food.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] A smaller number of species are farmed commercially.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Humans and their livestock make up more than 90% of the biomass of all terrestrial vertebrates, and almost as much as all insects combined.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Invertebrates including cephalopods, crustaceans, insects—principally bees and silkworms—and bivalve or gastropod molluscs are hunted or farmed for food, fibres.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Chickens, cattle, sheep, pigs, and other animals are raised as livestock for meat across the world.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animal fibres such as wool and silk are used to make textiles, while animal sinews have been used as lashings and bindings, and leather is widely used to make shoes and other items.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals have been hunted and farmed for their fur to make items such as coats and hats.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Dyestuffs including carmine (cochineal), shellac, and kermes have been made from the bodies of insects.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Working animals including cattle and horses have been used for work and transport from the first days of agriculture.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals such as the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* serve a major role in science as experimental models.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals have been used to create vaccines since their discovery in the 18th century.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Some medicines such as the cancer drug trabectedin are based on toxins or other molecules of animal origin.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] People have used hunting dogs to help chase down and retrieve animals, and birds of prey to catch birds and mammals, while tethered cormorants have been used to catch fish.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Poison dart frogs have been used to poison the tips of blowpipe darts.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] A wide variety of animals are kept as pets, from invertebrates such as tarantulas, octopuses, and praying mantises, reptiles such as snakes and chameleons, and birds including canaries, parakeets, and parrots all finding a place.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] However, the most kept pet species are mammals, namely dogs, cats, and rabbits.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] There is a tension between the role of animals as companions to humans, and their existence as individuals with rights of their own.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] A wide variety of terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sport.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The signs of the Western and Chinese zodiacs are based on animals.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] In China and Japan, the butterfly has been seen as the personification of a person's soul, and in classical representation the butterfly is also the symbol of the soul.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals have been the subjects of art from the earliest times, both historical, as in ancient Egypt, and prehistoric, as in the cave paintings at Lascaux.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Major animal paintings include Albrecht Dürer's 1515 *The Rhinoceros*, and George Stubbs's c.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Insects, birds and mammals play roles in literature and film, such as in giant bug movies.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Animals including insects and mammals feature in mythology and religion.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] The scarab beetle was sacred in ancient Egypt, and the cow is sacred in Hinduism.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/animal] Among other mammals, deer, horses, lions, bats, bears, and wolves are the subjects of myths and worship.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Antioquia borders the Córdoba department and the Caribbean Sea to the north; Chocó to the west; the departments of Bolívar, Santander, and Boyaca to the east; and the departments of Caldas and Risaralda to the south.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Medellín is Antioquia's capital and the second-largest city in the country.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Other important towns are Rionegro located in the East, Apartadó on the Caribbean Coast, Santa Fe de Antioquia, the old capital on the Cauca River, and Puerto Berrío on the Magdalena.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Antioquia is the sixth-largest department of Colombia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] It is predominantly mountainous, crossed by the Cordillera Central and the Cordillera Occidental of the Andes.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The Cordillera Central divides to form the Aburrá valley, in which the capital, Medellín, is located.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The Cordillera Central forms the plateaus of Santa Rosa de Osos and Rionegro.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] While 80% of the department's territory is mountainous, Antioquia also has lowlands in Bajo Cauca, Magdalena Medio, and eastern Sonsón, as well as coastline on the Caribbean Sea, in Urabá.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] This area has a tropical climate and is of high strategic importance due to its location.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The basis for the name Antioquia is uncertain.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] A common explanation is that it was named after the Hellenistic-founded city in Syria of Antioch on the Orontes (Greek: Ἀντιόχεια *Antiocheia*, Arabic: *Antāqiyyah*, now officially Antakya, Turkey).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The region of Colombia known as the Coffee Zone has a strong influence from Arab Jews, both demographically and culturally, and many towns and cities are named after cities in the Middle East.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Moreover, ancient Antioch played a significant role in developing the communities of early Christianity and thus was important to the Catholic Spaniard conquistadors.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] There are many other cities in the Middle East named Antiochia, which were likewise named for the Antiochid rulers during the Seleucid Empire (312–63 BC).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Before Spanish colonization, Indigenous peoples inhabited the Antioquia region.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Some specialists believe they came from Caribbean Sea, while others say they came from the interior Amazon River.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Antioquia was primarily populated by the Kalina or "Mainland Caribs." Some scattered groups of Muisca were said to be present in the Darién region, a coastal region in the far north that is now in Panama, but no historical records refer to Muisca in Antioquia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The Kalina in Antioquia comprised smaller groups called families.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The most prominent were the Catía, Nutabe, and Tahamí, who inhabited central Antioquia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The Quimbaya occupied southern Antioquia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The Quimbaya, Kalina, and Muisca were the most prominent groups the conquistadores encountered upon their arrival in Antioquia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The Spaniards had a turbulent history of encounters with the Carib.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Although the tribe was numerous and known for its warring culture, the Spaniards dominated or exterminated them in the process of conquest and colonization.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Like all indigenous peoples of the Americas, many died in virgin soil epidemics of diseases endemic to Eurasia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Some surviving natives dispersed to evade the Spanish, and some committed suicide to escape slavery.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Many survivors fled to what is now Chocó department.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Barely 0.5% of Antioquia's population is Indigenous, but most residents have a significant Indigenous genetic component (26% on average).
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Spain's Basque Country and Jews have influenced Antioquia and its language since the Spanish colonization.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] This began in 1499 during the third voyage of Columbus.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The owner and master of the *Santa María*, second in command to Columbus, was Juan de la Cosa, nicknamed *el Vizcaino* ("the Biscayan").
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Hundreds of Basques settled in the area, sponsored by the Spanish colonization companies.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] It has been asserted since the mid-nineteenth century that Basque and Jewish origins have influenced the character of Antioquia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Specific evidence of cultural contribution is sparse, perhaps partly because Basque is not dominant in Spain.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] However, American historian Everett Hagen sampled the Medellín telephone directory in 1957 and found that 15% of the surnames were of Basque origin, but 25% of the employers were.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] He concluded that Basque influence was important in explaining the increased industrial development of Antioquia in Colombia.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The study reinforced notions of the character of social groups, though it has been criticized as stereotypical.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The first Spaniard known to have visited the territory now known as Antioquia was Rodrigo de Bastidas, who explored the area around the future site of Darién in 1500.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Ten years later, Alonso de Ojeda founded San Sebastián de Urabá, 2 km from the present-day town of Necoclí.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The first Spanish military incursion into Antioquia, however, was not made until 1537.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] An expedition commanded by Francisco César traveled through the lands of chief Dabeiba, arriving at the Cauca River.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] They were said to have taken important treasures from the indigenous people's tombs.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] In response, the warriors of chief Nutibara harassed the Spaniards continually, and forced them to return to Urabá.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] In 1541, the conquistador Jorge Robledo departed from the site of the future (1542) Spanish town of Arma, a little below Aguadas in the North of Caldas, to lead an expedition north on the Cauca River.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Farther north, Robledo would found the city of Santa Fe de Antioquia, which in 1813 was declared the capital of the sovereign and independent state of Antioquia, and remained the seat of the governate until 1826, when Medellín was designated the capital.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Due to its geographical isolation, being located among mountains, Antioquia suffered supply problems.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Its topography did not allow for much agriculture, so the city became dependent upon trade, especially of gold and gin for the colonization of new land.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Much of this trade was due to reforms passed after a 1785 visit from Juan Antonio Mon y Velarde, an inspector of the Spanish Crown.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The Antioquia became colonizers and traders.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The department was hard hit by the Colombian conflict, with 30,000 people missing between 1997 and 2005.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Antioquia is divided into nine subregions to facilitate the Department's administration.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] These nine regions contain a total of 125 municipalities.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] The population of Antioquia is 6,994,792 (2023), of which more than half live in the metropolitan area of Medellín.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] During the 16th and 18th centuries, Antioquia received many immigrants from Spain, especially northern Spain.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Most Indigenous peoples died from the introduction of European diseases, and many of those who survived intermarried with early Spanish settlers, who were mostly men; later, Spanish women also began to immigrate.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Thousands of Scottish and English who settled in Antioquia fought for the Colombian army during independence.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] During the 19th and 20th centuries, immigrants (including Jews) arrived from Italy, Germany, United Kingdom, France, Portugal, Lebanon, Israel, Palestine and Syria.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] Many people from Antioquia are referred to as Paisas, people of mainly Spanish ancestry, a lot of them Basque.
[src:andinobates-cassidyhornae/antioquia-department] There is a small Afro-Colombian and Zambo-Colombian (people of Indigenous and African descent) population originating in the majority of the Urabá subregion and the neighboring departments of Chocó, Córdoba and Sucre.
